<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920107-0036</DOCNO><DOCID>920107-0036.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Berry Petroleum Co.:   Company Buys Some Assets   From Atlantic Richfield Co.</HL><DATE>01/07/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   ARC BRY</CO><MS>ENERGY (ENE)</MS><IN>OIL-INTEGRATED MAJORS (OIL)OIL-SECONDARY (OIS)PETROLEUM (PET)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><NS>PETROLEUM MARKET (PET)ACQUISITIONS andamp; MERGERS, TAKEOVERS, BOARD BATTLES (TNM)</NS><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Berry Petroleum Co. of Taft, Calif., said it acquiredcertain California oil and natural gas assets and a 50%interest in the Rincon Field in Ventura County, Calif., fromAtlantic Richfield Co.   In exchange for the properties and $2.9 million, BerryPetroleum said, Arco is relieved of its future explorationand development commitments in the Rincon Field, which theLos Angeles company owns jointly with Berry Petroleum. Thefield produces about 600 barrels of oil a day.</LP><TEXT>   &quot;Their {Arco's} corporate goals and ours are different,&quot;says Harvey L. Bryant, Berry Petroleum's chief executiveofficer. &quot;We still want to pursue the Rincon development.They don't.&quot; An Arco spokesman said: &quot;We had a largecommitment in a project with a small payout.&quot;   Berry Petroleum will acquire several properties in theMidway-Sunset Field in Kern County, Calif., representingabout 4% of Arco's current production in that field.   Berry said the acquisition would increase its currentproduction to about 12,000 barrels a day from about 10,000barrels a day and boost proven reserves to about 80 millionbarrels from 74 million.</TEXT></DOC>